  "description": "Let WW be a nonempty set.\nDefinition. A Kripke frame is a pair F=(W,R)\\mathcal{F} = (W, R), where WW is a set of possible worlds and R⊆W×WR \\subseteq W \\times W is an accessibility relation on WW.\nA frame carries no information about which propositions hold at which worlds. Adding a valuation V ⁣:Prop→P(W)V \\colon \\mathrm{Prop} \\to \\mathcal{P}(W) yields a Kripke model (W,R,V)(W, R, V).\nDefinition. A modal formula φ\\varphi is valid on the frame F\\mathcal{F}, written F⊨φ\\mathcal{F} \\models \\varphi, if for every valuation VV and every w∈Ww \\in W, (W,R,V),w⊨φ(W, R, V), w \\models \\varphi.\n",
  "name": "Kripke Frame",
